  "body": " A farmer wants to start raising cows, horses, goats, and sheep, and desires to have a rectangular pasture for the animals to graze in. However, no two different kinds of animals can graze together. In order to minimize the amount of fencing she will need, she has decided to enclose a large rectangular area and then divide it into four equally sized pens by adding three segments of fence inside the large rectangle that are parallel to two existing sides. She has decided to purchase 7500 ft of fencing. What is the maximum possible area that each of the four pens will enclose?   The maximum possible area that each of the four pens can enclose is 351562.5 square feet.   The farmer will fence a rectangular area whose length and width are unknown. The total area of the rectangular area is composed of 4 equal area rectangles. There are two ways to do this as shown in the figure below (though only the one on the left explicitly follows the way the problem is framed).     We want to maximize the area of each subrectangular region, which is the same as maximizing the total area of the entire rectangular region. Since has two variables, we can't yet directly apply calculus techniques to it. We use the information about the amount of fencing to relate and in order to write in terms of just one variable.  In the case of the fencing option on the left in the figure, the total amount of fencing that is needed to enclose the four grazing areas is . We assume that all of the feet of fencing will be used, so . Solving for , . Substituting this expression for into the area formula allows us to write in terms of alone: . To enclose any area, we of course must have and , and since , it follows that we need to have so . To find the maximum value of on this domain, we find the critical numbers of . Since , we see that when and only when . For , we see that and for we have . So square feet is the absolute maximum value of . The maximum possible area that each of the four pens can enclose is one quarter of the total, or square feet.  In the case of the fencing option on the right in the figure, the total amount of fencing that is needed to enclose the four grazing areas is . We assume that all of the feet of fencing will be used, so . Solving for and substituting into , we find and . To enclose any area, we of course must have and , and since , it follows that we need to have . To find the maximum value of on this domain, we find the critical numbers of . Since , we see that when and only when . For , we see that and for we have . So square feet is the absolute maximum value of . The maximum possible area that each of the four pens can enclose is one quarter of the total, or square feet.  So the maximum possible area that each of the four pens can enclose is 390625 square feet, and we see that the righthand alternative is even more optimal than the left one.  "
