  "body": " For the town of Mathland, MI, residential power consumption has shown certain trends over recent years. Based on data reflecting average usage, engineers at the power company have modeled the town's rate of energy consumption by the function .  Here, measures time in hours after midnight on a typical weekday, and is the rate of consumption in megawatts The unit megawatt is itself a rate, which measures energy consumption per unit time. A megawatt-hour is the total amount of energy that is equivalent to a constant stream of 1 megawatt of power being sustained for 1 hour. at time . Units are critical throughout this problem.   Sketch a carefully labeled graph of on the interval [0,24] and explain its meaning. Why is this a reasonable model of power consumption?    Without calculating its value, explain the meaning of . Include appropriate units on your answer.    Determine the exact amount of energy Mathland consumes in a typical day.    What is Mathland's average rate of power consumption in a given 24-hour period? What are the units on this quantity?         The model is reasonable because it appears to be periodic and the rate of consumption seems to peak at the times of day where people are most active in their homes.       The total energy consumed in hours, measured in megawatt-hours.     megawatt-hours of power used in hours.    megawatt-hours.        In the following plot, we see that the model is reasonable because it appears to be periodic and repeats every hours, as well as that the rate of consumption seems to peak at the times of day where people are most active in their homes: around a.m. and around p.m.       The meaning of is the total power consumed in hours, measured in megawatt-hours. This is because is measured in megawatts and in hours, and thus in the Riemann sum that corresponds to the definite integral, the terms in the sum of the form have units ``megawatt-hours''. Moreover, by integrating the rate of power consumption we get the total change in power consumed.    In a typical day, we know that Mathland consumes megawatt-hours of power, and thus we seek to evaluate the integral . To do so, we use the subtitutions (so ) and (so ) to help us antidifferentiate the two trigonometric expressions, and thus we find that and . Putting this all together and using the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, we have megawatt-hours of power used in hours.   We know that the average value of the rate function on is . Thus, by our work in (c), we have that which is measured in megawatts.    "
