  "body": " Let be the number of thousands of mice that live on a farm; assume time is measured in years. This problem is based on an ecological analysis presented in a research paper by C.S. Hollings: The Components of Predation as Revealed by a Study of Small Mammal Predation of the European Pine Sawfly, Canadian Entomology  91 : 283-320.   The population of the mice grows at a yearly rate that is twenty times the number of mice. Express this as a differential equation.    At some point, the farmer brings cats to the farm. The number of mice that the cats can eat in a year is thousand mice per year. Explain how this modifies the differential equation that you found in part a).    Sketch a graph of the function for a single cat and explain its features by looking, for instance, at the behavior of when is small and when is large.    Suppose that . Find the equilibrium solutions and determine whether they are stable or unstable. Use this to explain the long-term behavior of the mice population depending on the initial population of the mice.    Suppose that . Find the equilibrium solutions and determine whether they are stable or unstable. Use this to explain the long-term behavior of the mice population depending on the initial population of the mice.    What is the smallest number of cats you would need to keep the mice population from growing arbitrarily large?          .         For positive near , ; for large values of , .    The only equilibrium solution is , which is unstable.    The equilibrium solutions are (stable) and (unstable).    At least cats.         If we let be the population of the mice at year in thousands and it grows at a yearly rate that is twenty times the number of mice, the governing differential equation is .    On their own, the mice add thousand mice per year to their total population. With cats present, the cats now remove thousand mice per year. By taking both the rates at which mice are added and removed from the population into account, we find the updated differential equation     For positive near , ; for large values of , . This means that a single cat can remove about thousand mice per year from the population when the mice population is large.    Letting , we are working with the differential equation . To find the equilibrium solutions, we first set . Doing so, we find that , so , or . Factoring, we see and therefore or . Since a negative equilibrium solution doesn't make sense in the context of the problem, the only equilibrium solution to study is . If we plot versus for , we see that is always positive, and thus the population will grow away from , making this equilibrium unstable. And this makes sense: the population of mice will grow without bound, because one cat is insufficient to keep up with a mice population growing at a rate of times its size per year.    Letting , we are working with the differential equation . Similar work as in (d) shows that the equilibrium solutions are or , and if we plot versus , we see that for , , while for , . Thus, with cats present, as long as there are initially fewer than mice, the cats will drive the mice population to . If there are more than mice initially present, the mice population will grow without bound. And if there are mice initially present, this will be an (unstable) equilibrium.    In order to keep the mice population from growing arbitrarily large, we need to bring enough cats that for certain initial mice populations, we can make . In other words, we need enough cats that there's a positive equilibrium solution. Considering the general differential equation, , we thus set and solve for . Doing so, we find that , so or . Factoring, we find that . To have a positive equilibrium solution, we require that , and therefore the farmer must bring at least cats to the farm. Even in that circumstance, whether the cats can keep the number of mice from growing without bound will depend on the initial number of mice present.     "
